msgstr ""

#. type: Yaml Front Matter Hash Value: title
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Tutorial: How to become REUSE-compliant"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
msgid ""
"This tutorial explains the basics of making a software project REUSE-"
"compliant.  The goal is to **easily, comprehensively, and unambiguously** "
"declare your copyright and licensing in a way that is **machine-readable**. "
"By the end of this tutorial, you will understand the three fundamental steps "
"of REUSE:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1. '
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
msgid "Choose and provide licenses"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2. '
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
msgid "Add copyright and license information to each file"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '3. '
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
msgid "Confirm REUSE compliance"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
msgid ""
"For the purpose of this tutorial, we will assume that the directory of your "
"project looks like this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"project/\n"
"├── src/\n"
"│   └── main.c\n"
"├── Makefile\n"
"└── README.md\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
msgid ""
"If you would like to reproduce the steps in this tutorial on your own "
"computer, you can clone the [example repository](https://codeberg.org/fsfe/"
"reuse-tutorial-example). The branch `non-compliant` matches the structure "
"above, while the `compliant` branch is the successful result of this "
"tutorial."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
msgid ""
"For each of these steps, you will first learn how to achieve them manually.  "
"However, the [REUSE tool](https://codeberg.org/fsfe/reuse-tool) supports you "
"with most tasks, and the necessary commands will be listed as well in the "
"collapsible boxes. We recommend to first understand the basic principle "
"before just executing the tool's commands."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The first thing you need to do is to [choose a license]({{< relref\n"
"\"faq.md#which-license\" >}}). For this tutorial, we assume that you chose the GNU\n"
"General Public License (GPL) v3.0 or any later version. More than simply\n"
"choosing a license, you need to put the license in your project directory.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
msgid ""
"Find your license in the [SPDX License List](https://spdx.org/licenses/). "
"SPDX is an open standard for communicating license and copyright "
"information. Each license is uniquely identified by a shortform SPDX License "
"Identifier. The SPDX License Identifier for your chosen license is `GPL-3.0-"
"or-later`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
msgid ""
"Create a `LICENSES/` directory in your project root which will contain all "
"the licenses that you use in your project. In your case, this means creating "
"a file `GPL-3.0-or-later.txt` in this directory, which will contain the full "
"license text. The name of the file is an SPDX License Identifier. You can "
"find the license text for many Free Software licenses in the [license-list-"
"data](https://github.com/spdx/license-list-data/tree/master/text)  "
"repository."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "{{< box-tool >}}\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
msgid ""
"[The `reuse download` command](https://reuse.readthedocs.io/en/stable/man/"
"reuse-download.html) enables you to download a specific license. `reuse "
"download GPL-3.0-or-later` would fulfil the task described in the manual "
"instructions above. Running `reuse download --all` automatically downloads "
"all licenses which the REUSE tool detects as being used in your project."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "{{< /box-tool >}}\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
msgid ""
"Now that you have a license, you need to indicate in the relevant files that "
"these files fall under that license. Edit the comment header of `src/main.c` "
"as such:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"/*\n"
" * SPDX-FileCopyrightText: 2024 Jane Doe <jane@example.com>\n"
" *\n"
" * SPDX-License-Identifier: GPL-3.0-or-later\n"
" */\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The `SPDX-FileCopyrightText` tag records the publication years and copyright\n"
"holder of the contents of the file. You can read more about [which publication\n"
"years to use]({{< relref \"faq.md#years-copyright\" >}}) and [what copyright\n"
"holders are]({{< relref \"faq.md#copyright-holder-author\" >}}) in the FAQ.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
msgid ""
"The `SPDX-License-Identifier` tag is followed by a [valid SPDX License "
"Expression](https://spdx.org/specifications), typically just the SPDX "
"License Identifier of the license."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
msgid ""
"Each file must always contain these two tags in the header. You are allowed "
"to use the `SPDX-FileCopyrightText` tag multiple times if you have multiple "
"copyright holders."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
msgid ""
"In the example project, you also edit `Makefile` and `README.md` using this "
"header information, but of course with corresponding comment syntax."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
msgid ""
"[The `reuse annotate` command](https://reuse.readthedocs.io/en/stable/man/"
"reuse-annotate.html) helps with adding licensing and copyright information "
"to your files. For the task above, the following command will do the job:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "reuse annotate --copyright=\"Jane Doe <jane@example.com>\" --license=\"GPL-3.0-or-later\" src/main.c Makefile README.md\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
msgid ""
"Having added a license to your repository and having added copyright and "
"licensing information to each file, your project tree will now look like "
"this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"project/\n"
"├── LICENSES/\n"
"│   └── GPL-3.0-or-later.txt\n"
"├── src/\n"
"│   └── main.c\n"
"├── Makefile\n"
"└── README.md\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
msgid ""
"To ensure that you did not miss anything, you should confirm REUSE "
"compliance with the REUSE tool. Follow the [installation instructions]"
"(https://reuse.readthedocs.io/en/latest/readme.html#install)  available for "
"multiple platforms, then go to the project directory and run the linter."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ reuse lint\n"
"\n"
"# SUMMARY\n"
"\n"
"* Bad licenses: 0\n"
"* Deprecated licenses: 0\n"
"* Licenses without file extension: 0\n"
"* Missing licenses: 0\n"
"* Unused licenses: 0\n"
"* Used licenses: GPL-3.0-or-later\n"
"* Read errors: 0\n"
"* Files with copyright information: 3 / 3\n"
"* Files with license information: 3 / 3\n"
"\n"
"Congratulations! Your project is compliant with version 3.2 of the REUSE Specification :-)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
msgid ""
"As you can see in the last line, the tool confirms that your project is "
"compliant with REUSE now! To learn what the different criteria mean, please "
"have a look at the [documentation of the lint command](https://reuse."
"readthedocs.io/en/stable/man/reuse-lint.html)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "More information"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This tutorial was a lightning-quick introduction to REUSE. Not all use-cases are\n"
"covered here, especially [how to annotate uncommentable files]({{< relref\n"
"\"faq.md#uncommentable-file\" >}}), [how to bulk-annotate files]({{< relref\n"
"\"faq.md#bulk-license\" >}}), and [how to use a license not on the SPDX list]({{<\n"
"relref \"faq.md#custom-license\" >}}). In order to learn about these and more\n"
"practical use-cases, see the ['How do I ...' section in the Frequently Asked\n"
"Questions]({{< relref \"faq.md#howto\" >}}).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
msgid "Other sources for more information:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
msgid ""
"Our [Frequently Asked Questions](https://reuse.software/faq) covers common "
"questions as well as extraordinary cases and will constantly be updated."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
msgid ""
"The [REUSE Specification](https://reuse.software/spec) may aid you in "
"gaining a full understanding of REUSE."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: site/content/en/tutorial.md
msgid ""
"The [REUSE tool documentation](https://reuse.readthedocs.io/) describes "
